\begin_layout Subsection
Optimizing common pilot channel power
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Common Pilot Channel (CPICH) is used as reference for handover 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "umts_world:handover"

\end_inset

, cell selection 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "3glteinfo:cellSelection"

\end_inset

, and cell reselection 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "flore2005:cell_reselection"

\end_inset

.
 Whenever a mobile phone is switched on, it tries to register with the cell
 providing the highest received CPICH level.
 It also defines the effective coverage area of the cell: according to the
 the CPICH power level, the cell coverage area will enlarge or shrink.
 Consequently, by appropriately adjusting the CPICH power at the base stations,
 the number of served users per cell can be balanced among neighboring cells.
 This procedure is called load balancing and it reduces interference, stabilizes
 network operation, and facilitates radio resource management 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "WCDMAforUMTS_RadioAccessForThirdGenerationMobileCommunications"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Proposed solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chen and Yuan 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CPICH.optimization:2008"

\end_inset

 optimize CPICH transmit power starting from a uniform allocation (i.e.
 all cells are set with the same transmit power level).
 Their objective is to enhance HSDPA performance at cell edges while preserving
 control of R99 soft handover 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wiki:soft_handover"

\end_inset

.
 The solution approach is based on a linear-integer mathematical model.
 A very similar problem and proposed solution is presented by Siomina and
 Yuan 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CPICH.optimization:2007"

\end_inset

.
 The problem definition slightly differs from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CPICH.optimization:2008"

\end_inset

 as there is no reference to soft handover control.
 The solution is also implemented as a linear program.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Olmos et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CPICH.optimization:2003"

\end_inset

 apply simulated annealing to the optimization of CPICH transmit powers
 in order to force mobile phones to transmit to the best available cell
 in a service area.
 Their results show decreased cell load with a consequently increased network
 capacity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chen and Yuan 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CPICH.optimization:2009"

\end_inset

 present a two-phase optimization algorithm for large-scale mobile networks.
 The algorithm uses the total CPICH power consumption as a minimization
 objective.
 The authors claim that the tabu-search-based algorithm can compute near
 optimal solutions within a few seconds, even for large networks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Optimizing CPICH and antenna parameters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both the antenna tilt and azimuth directly affect the direction and range
 in which the cell broadcasts its CPICH.
 Consequently, optimal CPICH power is highly dependent on how the antenna
 tilt and azimuth are configured at base stations.
 Ideal configuration of antenna tilt and azimuth network-wise, with the
 objective of optimizing the CPICH power consumption, is a challenging task.
 For this reason, many authors have considered optimization methods that
 address all three parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Proposed solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Varbrand et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Coverage.optimization.on.CPICH.tilt.and.azimuth:2006"

\end_inset

 approach the optimization of service coverage (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Optimizing-coverage"

\end_inset

) by considering all three configuration parameters, namely: CPICH transmit
 power, antenna tilt, and antenna azimuth.
 Their simulated annealing algorithm searches the solution space of possible
 configurations in order to find improvements in network performance and
 total transmitted power.
 Interestingly, the algorithm is efficient enough to optimize large networks
 without using excessive computing resources.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Siomina 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CPICH.and.antenna.tilt.optimization:2005"

\end_inset

